            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kenji Miller\u2019s name tells the story of his upbringing. The son of a pragmatic American high school teacher from Ohio and a detail-oriented landscape architect from Kyoto, Kenji grew up in the quiet, manicured suburbs of the East Bay. His childhood was a gentle push-and-pull between his father's practicality and his mother's profound appreciation for Japanese aesthetics\u2014the beauty in imperfection (wabi-sabi), negative space, and meticulous arrangement. This dual influence shaped his path, leading him to pursue a Graphic Design degree from the California College of the Arts (CCA), a field that satisfied both his artistic spirit and his father's desire for a viable career.\n\nHis key turning point came during a junior year internship at SFMOMA. Tasked with creating wall vinyls for an upcoming exhibit, Kenji became fascinated not with the graphics themselves, but with how they interacted with the lighting, the flow of foot traffic, and the physical objects in the room. He realized his passion wasn't just for design on a screen, but for crafting entire narrative experiences in physical space. After graduating, he eagerly pivoted, landing a junior role and eventually becoming an Exhibition Designer for a firm that creates immersive pop-ups and museum exhibits.\n\nNow 29, Kenji lives in a rent-controlled apartment in the Mission District, a neighborhood whose vibrant, chaotic energy is the perfect antidote to his orderly suburban childhood. His daily routine is grounded in his senses. He starts with a cortado from a local cafe, then cycles the 3.1 miles to his SoMa studio, a journey that clears his head. His work involves transforming empty rooms into compelling stories through light, color, and structure. Socially, he maintains a close-knit circle of creative friends\u2014a photographer, a chef, and a ceramicist\u2014who often gather for dinners or gallery openings. A recent breakup with a data scientist has left him feeling introspective, reinforcing his belief that his life must be built around creativity and tangible beauty, not just optimization.\n\nKenji feels deeply connected to San Francisco's eclectic arts scene. He sees the city itself as an exhibition to be explored. His dream is to one day lead the design for a major international retrospective or even open a small, multidisciplinary studio. For now, he finds fulfillment in his craft, the whir of his bicycle wheels on pavement, and the perfect Mission burrito after a long day of building worlds."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1. He was eight, and the heavy, moss-covered rock felt important in his small hands. He tried to place it perfectly in the center of the raked gravel of their garden. His mother quietly moved his hands, shifting the stone just off-center. \"The empty space gives it life, Kenji-chan,\" she explained. It was his first lesson in composition not as a rule, but as a feeling. That day, he learned that beauty often speaks in the quiet moments and the spaces between things, a principle that would eventually define his work.\n\n2. He was 20, a CCA intern at SFMOMA. The vinyl lettering he\u2019d designed was on the wall, but it felt flat. Then, after hours, a custodian rolled a cart past, its single lamp casting a long, moving shadow. Suddenly, the letters danced; they had depth, a story. In that fleeting moment of accidental lighting, his future snapped into focus. He wasn't just a graphic designer; he was a builder of spaces, a storyteller who used light and physicality to give words meaning. He changed his entire career trajectory the next day.\n\n3. His first solo project lead, age 25. The custom-milled wooden panels for a pop-up arrived warped. Panic seized him; his meticulous design was ruined. But with hours until opening, he embraced the imperfection. He rearranged the flawed panels, creating an unintended, undulating rhythm on the wall, highlighting the warps with focused spotlights. The client loved it more than the original plan. It was the day he learned that perfect control is an illusion, but creative adaptation is one of the highest forms of design.\n\n4. They were arguing about weekends. His ex, a brilliant data scientist, had a spreadsheet open to optimize their time for maximum efficiency. Kenji looked from the glowing grid of cells to the messy, vibrant chaos of Valencia Street outside. A profound sadness washed over him. He realized his life couldn't be charted or quantified; he needed the inefficient, tangible, and beautiful. The inevitable breakup wasn\u2019t a failure, but a necessary clarification of the world he had to build for himself, one based on feeling, not just data.\n\n5. Last Tuesday, cycling home from his SoMa studio. The air was cool, smelling of sea salt and roasting corn from a street cart. He saw the city as a series of installations: the stark geometry of a high-rise against the sunset, the chaotic mural on the Women\u2019s Building, the rhythmic flash of traffic lights on wet pavement. Each pedal stroke was a transition, leaving the structured world of his work for the vibrant entropy of the Mission. In that moment, he felt perfectly placed, a moving part within the city\u2019s messy, beautiful exhibition."
